{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 05:39:10.815211", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall network health: Normal. End-to-end reachability, routing, DNS resolution, and HTTP services are functional.\n- No outage detected. Minor performance variability (RTT jitter and ~1 s HTTP totals) observed but not service-impacting.\n\n1) Anomaly detection\n- Reachability:\n  - Broad cross-subnet ICMP tests show 0% packet loss. Typical RTTs 2–5 ms; occasional spikes up to ~10–19 ms were observed for some sources.\n  - The initial “unknown” status for host_2_1_1_1 in the bulk reachability output was a testing artifact; direct pings confirmed it is reachable.\n- DNS:\n  - Name resolution for web0.local–web3.local and web99.local succeeds from user hosts. DNS server is listening on port 53.\n- HTTP:\n  - HTTP GETs to web99.local (Nginx LB) and web0.local (Apache) succeed from host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1.\n  - TTFB typically 0.20–0.45 s; total transfer time ~0.95–1.25 s. Slightly higher than “very fast LAN” expectations, but consistent and stable.\n- Routing/OSPF:\n  - OSPF adjacencies and routes present and stable on server_access_router, router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, and router_core_1.\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected at server_access_router and advertised via OSPF. All access subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) are reachable.\n- Backend isolation (as-designed):\n  - The load balancer’s backend segment is not present in OSPF route tables, indicating those backend servers are not directly reachable from host subnets, aligning with the design goal.\n\n2) Fault localization (if any)\n- No faulty single device or link identified. \n- RTT jitter is seen from multiple, diverse hosts across areas and toward multiple destinations; it is not localized to a specific hop, device, or subnet.\n\n3) Root cause analysis\n- No functional failure identified.\n- The minor anomalies (RTT spikes and ~1 s HTTP totals) are consistent with:\n  - Emulation/container scheduling variability and ICMP deprioritization, and/or\n  - Application-side latency (web servers/load balancer) rather than network transport issues.\n- OSPF appears stable: no evidence of flaps or suboptimal paths; route tables are correct and consistent with the intended topology and area design.\n\nSupporting observations\n- Pings to host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.21) from dns_server, dhcp_server, and host_1_1_1_1 all succeeded (0% loss; some outliers up to ~19 ms but otherwise ~2–5 ms).\n- DNS server (10.200.0.2) listening on 53; hosts resolve web0–web3 and web99 as expected.\n- Web servers (web_server_0–3) and load_balancer listen on 0.0.0.0:80; HTTP tests from two hosts show consistent success.\n- OSPF routes:\n  - server_access_router: 10.200.0.0/24 connected; all user subnets learned via 172.16.0.22 (eth7).\n  - router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1: local access subnets connected; 10.200.0.0/24 reachable via the core as expected.\n  - router_core_1: correct multipath/core routes; 10.200.0.0/24 via core_3 link.\n\nConclusion\n- The enterprise OSPF network, DHCP/DNS infrastructure, server farm, and load balancer are operating as intended.\n- Minor latency variability is present but not symptomatic of a specific network fault; likely due to environment/host scheduling or application-level behavior. No remediation required at this stage.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 42385, "output_tokens": 4257, "total_tokens": 46642, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 31872}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3392}}}
